1. Core abstraction

Every field is modeled as six things:

A. Nodes

The things that exist.

Examples:
	•	stores
	•	people
	•	neighborhoods
	•	ideas
	•	servers
	•	teams
	•	assets

B. Edges

The relationships between nodes.

Examples:
	•	proximity
	•	trade
	•	influence
	•	supply dependency
	•	communication
	•	competition
	•	alliance

C. Flows

What moves through the field.

Examples:
	•	people
	•	money
	•	goods
	•	energy
	•	attention
	•	trust
	•	information

D. Fields

Continuous background pressures.

Examples:
	•	demand
	•	fear
	•	prestige
	•	culture
	•	rent pressure
	•	regulation
	•	sentiment
	•	narrative gravity

E. Time

How all of the above change.

Examples:
	•	drift
	•	growth
	•	decay
	•	seasonality
	•	shocks
	•	phase changes

F. Operators

The actions an agent can take on the field.

Examples:
	•	place
	•	remove
	•	route
	•	cluster
	•	delay
	•	amplify
	•	dampen
	•	translate
	•	bridge
	•	segment

That is the base ontology.

⸻

2. What the engine does

The Field Engine has five jobs:

1. Observe

Ingest structured and unstructured data about the field.

2. Represent

Turn raw data into a common field model.

3. Infer

Estimate hidden structure:
	•	latent clusters
	•	bottlenecks
	•	attractors
	•	fragility
	•	momentum
	•	likely futures

4. Simulate

Test actions against the field before acting.

5. Recommend

Suggest moves that improve position, coordination, or resilience.

So:

world state → field representation → scenario testing → action ranking

