6. Core scoring system

The Field Engine should not just score “best.”
It should score what kind of best.

A. Position Score

How favorable is this placement in the current field?

Measures:
	•	access to flows
	•	low friction
	•	exposure to desirable pressure gradients
	•	low collision with dominant negatives

B. Coordination Score

How much does this move improve the fit among parts?

Measures:
	•	complementarity
	•	sequencing quality
	•	cluster reinforcement
	•	bridge creation
	•	reduced internal conflict

C. Resilience Score

How well does this survive shocks?

Measures:
	•	redundancy
	•	volatility exposure
	•	dependency concentration
	•	adaptability
	•	reversal cost

D. Momentum Score

How well does this align with the direction the field is already moving?

Measures:
	•	trend fit
	•	timing
	•	narrative current
	•	growth drift
	•	adoption pressure

E. Sovereignty / Control Score

How much freedom of action remains after the move?

Measures:
	•	lock-in risk
	•	fragility to counterparties
	•	switching cost
	•	reliance on external gates

F. Confidence Score

How much should you trust the recommendation?

Measures:
	•	data coverage
	•	model agreement
	•	analog quality
	•	recentness
	•	variance

